{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.06,0.03,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44583"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset shortness of breath and left-sided pleuritic chest pain. He has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, heart failure and type 2 diabetes. His medications include inhalers, bisoprolol, furosemide, spironolactone, and diabetes medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 135/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, oxygen saturation 84% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. ECG shows sinus tachycardia. Arterial blood gas reveals type 1 respiratory failure. Chest X-ray shows clear lung fields. A CT pulmonary angiogram is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would be expected on his CT pulmonary angiogram?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Filling defects within pulmonary arteries","Ground-glass opacities","Mosaic attenuation pattern","Pulmonary arterial dilatation","Right ventricular dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of pulmonary embolism (PE): sudden onset dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, hypoxaemia, and type 1 respiratory failure. The clinical presentation and investigation findings strongly suggest PE as the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFilling defects within pulmonary arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are the characteristic radiological finding in acute PE on CT pulmonary angiography. These appear as low-density areas within contrast-enhanced pulmonary arteries, representing thrombi that obstruct blood flow. The location and extent of these filling defects correlate with the severity of the PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGround-glass opacities\u003C/strong\u003E are a non-specific finding that appears as hazy increased lung opacity without obscuring bronchial and vascular margins. While they can occasionally be seen in PE due to pulmonary infarction or haemorrhage, they are more commonly associated with interstitial lung diseases, infections (particularly viral pneumonia), or pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMosaic attenuation pattern\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a patchwork of areas of differing attenuation on CT imaging. While this can be seen in chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension, it is not a typical finding in acute PE. It is more commonly associated with small airways disease or chronic pulmonary vascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary arterial dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E is a finding associated with pulmonary hypertension, which can develop as a chronic complication of PE but is not typically seen in acute PE. Pulmonary arterial dilatation develops over time in response to increased pulmonary vascular resistance and pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricular dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E can occur as a consequence of acute PE due to increased right ventricular afterload from pulmonary arterial obstruction. While CTPA can show right ventricular enlargement in severe PE, functional assessment of the right ventricle is better evaluated with echocardiography rather than CTPA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of PE is supported by the patient\u0027s presentation with sudden onset symptoms, hypoxaemia, and type 1 respiratory failure (low PaO2 with normal or low PaCO2) due to ventilation-perfusion mismatch. Risk factors in this patient include reduced mobility and chronic medical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Filling defects within pulmonary arteries are the characteristic finding on CT pulmonary angiography in acute pulmonary embolism.","Acute pulmonary embolism typically presents with sudden onset dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, and hypoxaemia.","Type 1 respiratory failure (hypoxaemia with normal or low PaCO2) is characteristic of pulmonary embolism due to ventilation-perfusion mismatch."],"references":["Vyas V, Sankari A, Goyal A. Acute Pulmonary Embolism. [Updated 2024 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560551/","Moore AJE, Wachsmann J, Chamarthy MR, Panjikaran L, Tanabe Y, Rajiah P. Imaging of acute pulmonary embolism: an update. Cardiovasc Diagn Ther. 2018 Jun;8(3):225-243. doi: 10.21037/cdt.2017.12.01. PMID: 30057872; PMCID: PMC6039809. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6039809/","Mos IC, Klok FA, Kroft LJ, de Roos A, Huisman MV. Imaging tests in the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism. Semin Respir Crit Care Med. 2012 Apr;33(2):138-43. doi: 10.1055/s-0032-1311792. Epub 2012 May 30. PMID: 22648485. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22648485/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84125"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84125"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T21:41:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T21:42:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCoun